sblist.title: SERVICE BULLETIN LIST
sblist.para: The SB List reflects the incorporation status of Service Bulletins edited by: THALES Avionics S.A. (Vendor Code F9111).
The SB List has the following five columns to indicate SBs and their status:
?? SB number (SB No.) ?? This is the number of the SB. If no SB affects the manual content, the comment None is given.
?? SB Revision (SB Rev) ?? This is the revision number of the SB.
?? SB Subject?? This is the subject of the SB.
?? Modification state (MODIFICATION STATE) ?? This is the equipment part number - modification state of the unit.

?? Incorporation date (INSERTED Date) ?? SB status or incorporation date is indicated in this column as follow: If the SB is fully incorporated into the manual, the incorporation date is indicated. If the SB is partially incorporated into the manual, the field is left blank. If the SB data does not affect the manual content, the comment NO EFFECT is given.
?? Incorporation date (INSERTED No.) ?? This is the revision number of the updating Component Maintenance Manual (CMM).

unlitem.para: The Component Maintenance Manual (CMM) conforms to ATA Specification No. 2200.
The CMM provides shop verified procedures that enable a technician to restore the component to its serviceable condition in the overhaul shop.
The Abbreviated Component Maintenance Manual (ACMM) is a brief version of the CMM, for simple components which require periodic maintenance and/or testing.
The ACMM/CMM is prepared by the Manufacturer for each Repairable or Overhaulable unit.

THALES Avionics Technical Publications use both metric and non-metric system of measurement. The system used in the original reference documents is given first, followed by the conversion into the other system in brackets.
The information contained in the CMM has been divided into three main categories:
Description and Operation (DO),
Maintenance Procedure (MP),
Illustrated Parts List (IPL).
The table below gives the identifications (Pageblock) used for the three categories of data.

task.title: Maintenance Task Oriented Support System Task/Subtask numbering

prcitem.para: The functional arrangement of data and the numbering system form the basis for the assignment of maintenance Task/Subtask numbers to each maintenance operation (Task) described in the CMM. Task/Subtask numbers are mainly for the use of the Data management and have no significance for the reader of the CMM. The Introduction (INTRO) and the Description and Operation (DO) are broken down into Tasks. The Maintenance Procedures (MP) are broken down into Tasks and Subtasks.

unlitem.para: A TASK is defined as:
A maintenance work procedure which contains a sequence of work steps, which may be organised into Subtasks.
A block of data e.g. Description and Operation.
A table, an illustration or a multi-sheet illustration e.g. Figure x Sheets 1 through to 4 will all be part of one Task.

A SUBTASK is a single-skill work step or group of work steps within a Task, which provides detail of a significant part of the procedure. The completion of a SUBTASK must be possible in one location at one time.
The tag name is the word TASK, SUBTASK or GRAPHIC.
ATA number (six digits).
MTOSS function code (three digits).
It is used to indicate the particular maintenance function involved.
For each tag name, this code is selected from numbers 000 through 999 as listed in the table Pageblock Assignment.
Sequential number of the function code (three digits).
It enables a unique identification number to be allocated for all Tasks/Subtasks which are similarly numbered throughout the preceding elements.
Tasks and Subtasks are numbered differently:
Task idents begin at 801 and rise, sequentially, to 999 (maximum) within the procedure,
Subtask idents begin at 001 and rise, sequentially, to 800 (maximum) within the procedure.
Illustrations and Tables are considered as Tasks. These Task idents begin at 001 and rise, sequentially, to 999 (maximum) within the procedure.

note.para: If a particular Task or Subtask is deleted, the Task/Subtask number must not be re-used.

unlitem.para: Alphanumeric indicator (three characters):
the first character is a letter to indicate a different configuration due to different criteria configuration (modification, Service Bulletin(s), variations of work practices,...),
the second and third characters are digits to indicate alternative methods/techniques of maintenance.
Alphanumeric indicator (three characters).
It is to be assigned by an airline to highlight unique airline data.

caution.para: MAKE SURE THAT THERE IS NOT TOO MUCH WEIGHT ON THE CONTAINER, IF YOU PUT CONTAINERS ONE ON TOP OF THE OTHER, TOO MUCH WEIGHT ON THE CONTAINER CAN CAUSE DAMAGE TO THE COMPONENT.
DO NOT KEEP THE CONTAINER NEAR FLUIDS THAT CAN CAUSE CORROSION OR DAMAGE, AND DO NOT KEEP IT NEAR HEAT OR OZONE SOURCES.
For the optical fibers, use the precautions that follow:

unlitem.para: You must not move fibers when the room temperature is less than 2C.
The fibers and harness must be received, moved and stored in individual packages.
The termination of each optical contact must have a "RED" cap which can be used for overall protection measures that are set up against ESD.

Package harnesses must be kept at all times in a rigid tray or container that you can use to move and store them without strain, deformation and/or pressure (even locally). There must be no other items in the same package.
The protections and the package must give good protection against dust.
Put in storage in clean, sound areas that are not specially moist.
Remove the fibers from their package and individual protection on correct work stations (no desktop).
Remove items from packages only when they are necessary for use.

prcitem.para: Install the protection caps on the connector J1.
If the optical fibers are not connected to the OVM, make sure that protection caps protect the connectors of the optical fibers.
Do a visual check of the equipment before you put it in storage ().
Put the component in a cardboard box with internal anti-shock blocks and one desiccant bag. Close the box and seal the box edges with adhesive tape.
Put the identification labels on the component and on the external surface of the container. Make sure that:
The identification label has all the applicable data of the component.
You can read the labels easily.
Close the container.
Keep the container in a clean, dry room with a good supply of air.
Keep the room temperature between 15 degrees C (5 degrees F) and 50 degrees C (122 degrees F).
Keep the relative humidity to less than 85 per cent.
Put the container in a position where you can easily read the identification label.
No special precautions are necessary to send the component if its preservation is correct.
